  <h2>635 Nautical Miles</h2>

  <p>
    The Newport Bermuda Race is one of the oldest and most respected offshore sailing races in the world. Newport, Rhode Island to St. David's Head, Bermuda. 635 nautical miles across the Gulf Stream, with whatever weather the Atlantic decides to throw at you. It's been running since 1906.
  </p>

  <p>
    We're entering the 2026 edition. And we're bringing a 3D printer.
  </p>

  <h2>Why This Race</h2>

  <p>
    I've been saying for years that 3D printing belongs on boats. Not as a novelty — as a tool. When something breaks 300 miles from the nearest port, your options are limited: jury-rig a fix with what you've got, retire from the race, or print a replacement. We're going to prove that the third option is real.
  </p>

  <p>
    The Newport Bermuda Race is the right platform for this because it's serious offshore sailing with real conditions. The Gulf Stream crossing alone can produce violent weather. Parts break. Equipment fails. The race demands self-sufficiency, and a 3D printer is the ultimate self-sufficiency tool.
  </p>

  <h2>The Onboard Setup</h2>

  <p>
    We're working through the logistics of running a printer on a moving sailboat. The challenges are real:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Power:</strong> 12V marine electrical system. The printer needs stable power regardless of heel angle and battery state.</li>
    <li><strong>Motion:</strong> A boat at sea is never still. Pitch, roll, yaw — all of it affects print quality. We're developing mounting solutions that keep the printer functional in moderate conditions.</li>
    <li><strong>Space:</strong> Boats are small. Every square inch is contested. The printer has to earn its space against other gear.</li>
    <li><strong>Materials:</strong> We're bringing a curated selection of filaments — ASA, PETG-CF, and TPU — to cover the most likely repair scenarios.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Is every print going to be perfect? No. But it doesn't need to be perfect. It needs to be functional. A replacement sheave, a broken fairlead, a cracked instrument housing — these don't need to be show pieces. They need to work for the rest of the race.
  </p>

  <h2>What We're Proving</h2>

  <p>
    This campaign is about more than one race. It's about demonstrating that distributed manufacturing — making what you need, where you need it, when you need it — isn't science fiction. The technology exists today. The materials exist today. What's been missing is someone willing to actually do it in a demanding environment and document the results.
  </p>

  <p>
    If we can 3D print functional parts on a sailboat crossing the Gulf Stream, the conversation about onboard manufacturing changes permanently. Yacht outfitters, race teams, cruising sailors, naval operations — everyone with a vessel will have to reconsider what's possible.
  </p>

  <h2>Follow the Campaign</h2>

  <p>
    We'll be documenting everything. The build-up, the training, the onboard printer setup, and the race itself. Every part printed, every failure, every success. No sugarcoating.
  </p>

  <p>
    If you're in the sailing world, the 3D printing world, or you just want to watch someone try something that hasn't been done before — follow along. This is what 3D3D was built for. Taking printers where they haven't been and making parts where they're needed most.
  </p>

  <p>
    Newport to Bermuda. 635 miles. One printer. Let's see what happens.
  </p>
</BlogLayout>
